<statement>
<p>A triangle has sides with lengths <m>\displaystyle{a}={4.00}</m>, <m>\displaystyle{b}={6.55}</m>, and <m>\displaystyle{c}={7.97}</m>. Calculate all of the angles of this triangle.</p>
<p>A=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{a}={4.00}</m>)</p>
<p>
  B=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{b}={6.55}</m>)</p>
<p>
  C=<fillin characters="4"/> (across from side of length <m>\displaystyle{c}={7.97}</m>)</p>
<p>Round to two decimal places.</p>


</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li>30</li><li>54.95</li><li>94.15</li></ul></p><p>Because we have all three sides, we can use the law of cosines for the first angle.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{4}^{{2}}={6.55}^{{2}}+{7.97}^{{2}}-{2}{\left({6.55}\right)}{\left({7.97}\right)}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{16}={42.9025}+{63.5209}-{104.407}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{90.4234}=-{104.407}{\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{0.86606645148314}={\cos{{\left({A}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{A}={29.995295945756}={30}</m>.</p>
<p>For a second angle, we can use the shorter law of sines.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle\frac{{\sin{{\left({29.995295945756}\right)}}}}{{4.00}}=\frac{{\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}}{{6.55}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{1.6190720613051}={\sin{{\left({B}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={\arcsin{{\left(-{1.6190720613051}\right)}}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{B}={54.948241684186}\approx{54.95}</m></p>
<p>The third angle we can calculate using the angle sum property.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{29.995295945756}+{54.948241684186}+{C}={180}^{\circ}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{C}={94.153807539234}\approx{94.15}</m></p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>